Abstract

As a collection project of STA141A, this document is a report analysis derived from the exploration of a large set of data in neural activity for mice, and able to use the information and context of trials to form a predictive model. The goal is to predict models that allow us to forecast the outcome of different trials using different variables within the given dataset. After deciding on the final model, the student will be assigned to a new dataset to test the models performance.

Background

In this project, we will be assigned to analyze a dataset that was collected from Steinmetz, N.A., Zatka-Haas, P., Carandini, M. et al.Distributed coding of choice, action and engagement across the mouse brain. Nature 576, 266273 (2019).. In this study, the original set of data consists of 39 sessions worth of hundreds of experimental trials that were performed on 10 different mice. And the dataset we will be using will be performed on a total of 4 mice over 18 sessions, which these sessions rds also consisted of hundreds of trials. In the trials, these mice were randomly presented with visual stimuli on two different sides on either side of the mouse. These visual that were shown to each mouse will be present randomly in contrast levels that were labeled as (0, 0.25, 0.5, 1), where 0 means no stimuli. The mice will use a wheel controlled by their forepaws to make decisions regarding the provided stimuli. Depending on the decision made by the mouse, a reward or penalty was administered. Bases on the outcome of their decisions, they will be relatively given reward or penalty.

For our project, we will use data from 18 experimental sessions involving four mice named Cori, Forssmann, Hench, and Lederberg. Were analyzing the spike train data that represents the neuronal activity in the visual cortex of these mice, specifically capturing the neural firing from the stimulus onset to 0.4 seconds afterward.

The results indicate that both the mouse and the contrast difference are important factors to consider when looking at the success rates. The significant main effect for both mouse_name and contrast difference containsp_value of < 2e-16, which suggests that there are statistically significant differences in success rates among both the mice and contrast difference. This indicates that the identity of the mouse has a strong impact on the success rate. Additionally, the interaction between these two suggest that the contrast difference effect the success rate will be most likely vary on the mouse, in which we should consider the different adaptation, and sensitivity for each mouse.

Dimension Reduction through PCA

We perform PCA and visualize the 2D results.

## Importance of components:
##                           PC1    PC2    PC3    PC4    PC5     PC6     PC7
## Standard deviation     1.2967 1.1618 1.0625 1.0351 1.0111 0.87977 0.80457
## Proportion of Variance 0.2102 0.1687 0.1411 0.1339 0.1278 0.09675 0.08092
## Cumulative Proportion  0.2102 0.3789 0.5200 0.6540 0.7817 0.87850 0.95942
##                            PC8
## Standard deviation     0.56981
## Proportion of Variance 0.04058
## Cumulative Proportion  1.00000

The above summary table for the results from running a principal component analysis (PCA). The table provides the standard deviation, proportion of variance, and the cumulative of variance that is explained by the PC. The reason why we choose PC1 and PC2 to be our axis because if we use the remain pcs like PC3 and P4, the plot will not look as organized and distributed because the PC3,4 and others contains relatively smaller total variance.

These two plots analyze the neural activity or behavior in mice, with points representing trial outcomes across various sessions or mice. The first plot took color for session numbers(n.session), which it uses a gradient color changing to indicate the progression over each session. The lighter blue color represents later session like 15,16,17, which they seem to shift towards the right end of the PC2 axis, we can see that as color has changed brighther, and the dots have shift more towards the left top corner. Which could possibly demonstrate a evolution changed while time increases. For the second plot, it was colored for four color, and each represent a individual mouse name. It present a more scattered distribution on the plot. And we can see that the purple dot distribution(Lederberg) shift towards the end of PC2 at the left top corner, which seem to have a more compact distribution compared to the other mice. This indicate multiple potential factors, such like the adaptability and activity of different mice. Since principal components(PC1 and PC2) contains a majority of the total variance(0.2102, 0.1687), the figure above is a PCA plot with the pc1 on the x-axis and pc2 are on the y-axis. And we have used the 18 session and the 4 mice name to examing for this project. PC1 and PC2 for both 18 sessions and 4 mice name appear to create diagonally parallel shape with tails shift towards the end of PC2. But there is significant overlap in both plots, which indicate that the two PCS may not have a really strong association with the individual identities, session and mice. Instead, the distributed points might indicate the possibility other factors having more contribution to the vriables.

Using the logistic regression model to predict the outcomes, we observed the following results in the confusion matrix: there were 1990 values for actual 0 (negative class) and prediction 0 (correctly predicted negative), and 3619 values for actual 1 (positive class) and prediction 1 (correctly predicted positive). For the cases where the model predicted a positive outcome (1) but the actual outcome was negative (0), there were 939 instances. Similarly, for the cases where the model predicted a negative outcome (0) but the actual was positive (1), there were 3286 instances. This leads to an accuracy of 57.04% for the model, which indicates that slightly more than half of the predictions made by the model were correct. While this accuracy rate would be considered somewhat low in a grading scale context. But the reasons why I chose this model is that logistic regression has the relatively highest accuracy, comparing to all the other prediction methods, including SVM (0.5) and Random Forest (0.52). This highlights logistic regressions ability to provide a more broad understanding of the relationships between the predictors and the outcome, even in a really complex dataset.Logistic regression coefficients can be directly understood in terms of odds ratios, which offering clear insights into how each predictor influences the probability of the outcome. Which I think these coefficient helps me understanding the effect of variables, and I believe that is as important as the prediction accuracy itself. Although logistic regression was of great help to my understanding of this set of data, the unsatisfactory prediction accuracy indicates that there is room for improvement in the performance of this model. In short, although the logistic regression model provides certain predictive capabilities, I think its performance is comparable to other models I used.

Section 6 Discussions

In this project, we analyzed neural activity data from mice to predict experimental outcomes based on a variety of variables. The dataset consists of 18 sessions from four different mice and focuses on spike train data representing neuronal activity. We use R for data processing, exploratory analysis, and predictive modeling, combined with techniques such as data aggregation, PCA dimensionality reduction, and logistic regression for predictive modeling. Our exploratory analyzes revealed insights into neural activity, differences in brain regions engaged during trials, and differences in success rates across experiments and individual mice. We can observe significant differences in neural activity and success rates, suggesting differential differences in each mouses response to the trial. For predictive modeling, we used logistic regression, which was chosen for its ability to understand the impact of various predictors on the outcomes of different trials.. The model demonstrated moderate accuracy in predicting trial outcomes from different test prediction, although there were limitations in achieving high predictive performance across all sessions. In tests on separate data sets, the logistic regression model showed varying degrees of accuracy, suggesting that while it was less than ideal at predicting outcomes, there was still room for improvement. Factors such as data distribution, category characteristics, and data processing methods may affect model performance.
